'''Jorge Carlos Vergara Madrigal''' ({{IPA-es|'xoɾxe βeɾˈɣaɾa}}) (born 3 March 1955) is a Mexican businessman and film producer. Vergara is a [[billionaire]] 
with a net worth of approximately $1.5 billion. He is the founder of [[Grupo Omnilife]], one of the top 200 corporations in Mexico. 
In addition to its health products business, Grupo Omnilife owns the [[association football|football]] clubs [[Club Deportivo Guadalajara]] and Chivas Hefei, including a fleet of private jets and real estate.

Vergara has also produced internationally recognized films such as ''[[The Assassination of Richard Nixon]]'' and the Oscar-nominated ''[[Y tu mamá también]]'' through the production company, Producciones Anhelo.

==Career==

===Business===
Born in [[Guadalajara, Jalisco]], Vergara once sold tacos on Mexican streets. Back in the 1980s Vergara sold condominiums and timeshares in [[Manzanillo, Colima|Manzanillo]], Mexico, where he met and began working with John Peterson.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}

When Peterson became a [[Herbalife]] salesperson, he recruited Vergara and together they began selling Herbalife products in Mexico. Since Herbalife had not received Mexican government approval to sell their products, Peterson and Vergara had to smuggle the products into the country. After six months of smuggling the products into Mexico, Herbalife took notice and began the process of getting government approval. Vergara was asked to help get the Herbalife products approved by the Mexican government and was instrumental in helping Herbalife's founder, Mark Hughes deal with the Mexican Government. This gave Vergara insight into how a [[Multi-level marketing|multi-level company]] profits and expands into other countries.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Vergara was partners with Roger Daley, Jim Fobair and Charlie Ragus. With already the 51% of the company, Vergara acquired the rest of Omnitrition at the end of the deal with his U.S. partners and took the whole control of Omnitrition de Mexico.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Since its foundation in 1991, the privately owned corporation has grown from one company, Omnilife de Mexico, to comprise nineteen companies.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Today, approximately 5.2 million people distribute Omnilife products in 22 countries, while the company has reached annual sales of nearly $4.2 billion.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}

Vergara has been the director of Omnilife de Mexico since 1991.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/hispanicheritage2008/news/story?id=3642048 |title=Chivas USA holding its own in Southern California market - ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=15 October 2008 |accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>

===Film===
In 1999 Vergara met film director [[Alfonso Cuarón]] while seeking out filmmakers for his corporate movies. Cuarón, however, was more interested in filming ''[[Y tu mamá también]]'', and gave Vergara the screenplay. A known lover of films, Vergara read it and right away proposed that they begin production. In the process they established a production company [[Producciones Anhelo]] that would go on to co-produce [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s ''[[El Espinazo Del Diablo]]'' (''The Devil's Backbone''), along with [[Pedro Almodóvar]]'s [[El Deseo]] and del Toro's [https://www.imdb.com/company/co0040776/ Tequila Gang]. Anhelo also produced [[Sebastián Cordero]]'s ''[[Crónicas]]''.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}

In 2002, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' named Vergara one of its Ten Producers to Watch.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2002/scene/markets-festivals/10-to-watch-jorge-vergara-1117867479/|title=10 to Watch: Jorge Vergara|last=Tegel|first=Simeon|date=2002-05-14|work=Variety|access-date=2017-10-12|language=en-US}}</ref> For the 2004 edition of the [[Guadalajara Film Festival]], Vergara created the JVC Award for Best Director, which was given to Fernando Eimbcke for his feature debut [[Temporada de patos]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}

===Chivas===
Vergara gained ownership of the [[Association football|football]] team [[Club Deportivo Guadalajara]] (popularly known as ''Chivas'') in 2002. Shortly after he took ownership in Mexico, while attending the 2004 U.S. [[Major League Soccer]] All-Star Game, he announced intentions to expand Chivas to MLS.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}

Vergara and MLS inaugurated [[Chivas USA]] in 2004, and the team played its first official season in 2005 with [[StubHub Center]] in the Los Angeles area as its home stadium. Chivas USA was initially successful; in its first five seasons of operation, the team recorded four straight MLS playoff appearances.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> Both performance and attendance declined sharply after 2009.<ref name="Baxter">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-mls-chivas-usa-20130530,0,1160192.story|title=When will MLS save Chivas USA from itself?|last=Baxter|first=Kevin|date=30 May 2013|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref> In August 2012, Vergara and his former wife became sole owners of the club, buying out former partners Antonio and Lorenzo Cué.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2012/08/29/vergara-fuentes-become-sole-owners-chivas-usa |title=Vergara, Fuentes become sole owners of Chivas USA |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |date= |accessdate=8 August 2015}}</ref>

On 20 February 2014, Major League Soccer purchased Chivas USA from Vergara. They announced plans to sell to a buyer dedicated to keeping the club in Los Angeles, as well as a plan to rebrand the club.<ref>{{cite web|author=MLS Communications |url=http://www.mlssoccer.com/news/article/2014/02/20/major-league-soccer-purchases-chivas-usa |title=Major League Soccer purchases Chivas USA |publisher=MLSsoccer.com |date= |accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> The team, no longer affiliated with Vergara, has the working name [[Los Angeles Football Club]], and began MLS play in 2018.

==Personal life==
{{BLP unsourced section|date=October 2017}}
Vergara has six children: Yelena Vergara Zatarain, Amaury Vergara Zatarian, Kenya Vergara Zatarain, Uma Vergara Lerdo de Tejada, Valentina Vergara and Mariaignacia Vergara.

Jorge Vergara divorced Angélica Fuentes Téllez in 21 September 2015. Jorge Vergara and Rossana Lerdo de Tejada were married 10 June 2017 in Guadalajara, Jalisco, México.

